  "The rent vs. buy comparison ($1,500/mo rent vs. $1,800/mo mortgage) is more complex than just the $300 difference because buying also includes:": "",
  "Tax benefits and equity building, BUT also property taxes, insurance, maintenance, and opportunity cost of the down payment": "",
  "Only the tax benefits of homeownership under most circumstances involving rent": "",
  "Only the home appreciation when the interaction between rent and mortgage factors is taken into full account": "",
  "Nothing else — monthly payment is the only factor according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "A proper rent vs. buy analysis must include all costs: mortgage payment, property taxes, insurance, maintenance (1-2% of home value/year), opportunity cost of the down payment, and the benefits of equity building and potential appreciation.": "",
  "A $60,000 down payment invested at 8% instead of used for a home would grow to approximately _____ in 10 years.": "",
  "$60,000": "",
  "~$129,500": "",
  "$100,000": "",
  "$80,000": "",
  "$60,000 × 1.08^10 = $60,000 × 2.159 = $129,500. This is the opportunity cost of the down payment — money that could have been growing through investments instead of being locked in home equity.": "",
  "Car lease: $400/month for 36 months = $14,400 total. Buy: $500/month for 60 months, car worth $12,000 at end. Net cost of buying =": "",
  "$30,000": "",
  "$18,000": "",
  "$12,000": "",
  "$42,000": "",
  "Total buy payments = $500 × 60 = $30,000. Net cost = $30,000 - $12,000 resale = $18,000. While the net buy cost ($18,000) is more than one lease ($14,400), you own the car and can drive it payment-free afterward.": "",
  "Average new car depreciation: a $35,000 car is worth approximately _____ after 5 years.": "",
  "~$14,000": "",
  "$20,000": "",
  "$25,000": "",
  "$35,000": "",
  "Cars typically lose about 60% of their value in the first 5 years. $35,000 × 0.40 = $14,000. This rapid depreciation is why buying a 2-3 year old used car is often more financially prudent.": "",
  "College ROI: $100,000 in tuition for a degree that increases lifetime earnings by $900,000. Simple ROI =": "",
  "800%": "",
  "100%": "",
  "900%": "",
  "500%": "",
  "ROI = (Gain - Cost) / Cost = ($900,000 - $100,000) / $100,000 = 800%. This simple calculation overstates the true ROI because it ignores foregone earnings and the time value of money.": "",
  "Opportunity cost of 4 years in college instead of working at $35,000/year =": "",
  "$200,000": "",
  "$70,000": "",
  "$140,000": "",
  "Foregone earnings = $35,000 × 4 years = $140,000. This is income you could have earned but chose to forgo in order to attend college — a real economic cost that should factor into the ROI calculation.": "",
  "Adjusted college ROI including foregone earnings: ($900K - $100K - $140K) / ($100K + $140K) =": "",
  "~275%": "",
  "Net gain = $900K - $100K tuition - $140K foregone earnings = $660K. Total cost = $100K + $140K = $240K. Adjusted ROI = $660K / $240K = 275%. Still excellent, but more realistic than the simple 800% calculation.": "",
  "To accumulate $1.5 million by age 65 starting at age 25 (40 years) at 8% return, the required monthly savings is approximately:": "",
  "~$430": "",
  "$1,500": "",
  "$800": "",
  "$200": "",
