  "What is opportunity cost in financial decision-making?": "",
  "The value of the best alternative you give up when making a choice": "",
  "The hidden fees in a financial product": "",
  "The cost of missed investment opportunities due to market timing": "",
  "The actual dollar cost of a purchase": "",
  "Opportunity cost is the value of what you forgo when choosing one option over another. For example, using $60,000 as a down payment means forgoing the investment returns that money could have earned.": "",
  "What is the 4% withdrawal rule in retirement planning?": "",
  "You should keep 4% of your portfolio in cash under most circumstances involving retirement": "",
  "Your investments should earn at least 4% annually under most circumstances involving retirement": "",
  "A guideline stating you can withdraw 4% of your retirement portfolio annually (adjusted for inflation) with a high probability the money lasts 30 years": "",
  "You should save 4% of your income for retirement when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "The 4% rule (from the Trinity Study) suggests withdrawing 4% of your initial portfolio value annually, adjusted for inflation. This means you need 25 times your desired annual income saved for retirement.": "",
  "What is depreciation in the context of asset ownership?": "",
  "The decrease in an asset's value over time due to wear, age, or obsolescence": "",
  "The tax paid when selling an asset": "",
  "The increase in an asset's value over time": "",
  "The interest charged on an asset loan": "",
  "Depreciation is the loss of value over time. Cars, electronics, and equipment depreciate. In contrast, real estate and some collectibles may appreciate. Understanding depreciation is key to calculating the true cost of ownership.": "",
  "What does ROI (Return on Investment) measure?": "",
  "The market value of an investment portfolio": "",
  "The percentage gain or loss relative to the amount invested: (Gain - Cost) / Cost": "",
  "The annual dividend paid by an investment": "",
  "The total revenue generated by an investment": "",
  "ROI = (Net Gain - Cost) / Cost, expressed as a percentage. It is a universal metric for evaluating the efficiency of any investment — from education to real estate to business ventures.": "",
  "What does the 'time value of money' mean in personal finance?": "",
  "Money loses all value over time": "",
  "Time is more valuable than money": "",
  "You should only invest money for long time periods": "",
  "A dollar today is worth more than a dollar in the future because it can be invested to earn returns": "",
  "The time value of money is the foundational concept that money available now can earn interest, making it more valuable than the same amount received later. This principle drives all present value, future value, and discounting calculations.": "",
  "What is an emergency fund?": "",
  "A readily accessible cash reserve of 3-6 months of living expenses to cover unexpected financial setbacks": "",
  "A credit card kept only for emergencies": "",
  "A government program that provides unemployment benefits": "",
  "Money invested in high-risk stocks for quick gains": "",
  "An emergency fund is a liquid cash reserve (typically in a high-yield savings account) covering 3-6 months of expenses. It protects against job loss, medical bills, car repairs, and other unexpected costs without going into debt.": "",
  "What does 'dollar-cost averaging' mean?": "",
  "Converting foreign currencies to dollars at averaged exchange rates": "",
  "Investing a fixed dollar amount at regular intervals regardless of market price, which buys more shares when prices are low and fewer when high": "",
  "Splitting investments equally across all asset classes": "",
  "Investing all your money at once when the market is low": "",
  "Dollar-cost averaging removes the emotion of market timing. By investing consistently (e.g., $500/month), you automatically buy more shares when prices drop and fewer when prices rise, lowering your average cost over time.": "",
  "What is the difference between 'good debt' and 'bad debt'?": "",
  "Good debt has no interest; bad debt has interest, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "All debt is equally bad and should be avoided, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these debt dynamics operate": "",
  "The difference is only the lender's reputation due to the well-established relationship between debt trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "Good debt finances appreciating assets or increases earning power (mortgage, student loans); bad debt finances depreciating assets or consumption (credit cards, payday loans)": "",
  "Good debt has a low interest rate and builds wealth (mortgage, education). Bad debt has high interest rates and finances consumption (credit card balances, payday loans). The key test: does the debt help you build net worth over time?": "",
  "What is financial literacy?": "",
  "The ability to read financial news within the broader context of financial analysis": "",
  "The knowledge and skills needed to make informed and effective financial decisions throughout life": "",
  "Being wealthy considering that the key variables involved tend to move in this direction": "",
  "Having a finance degree when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Financial literacy encompasses understanding budgeting, saving, investing, debt management, insurance, and taxes — the skills needed to navigate every financial decision from the first paycheck through retirement.": "",
  "What does the 'pay yourself first' strategy mean?": "",
  "Start a business to create your own income": "",
  "Automatically set aside savings and investments before spending on anything else": "",
  "Pay off all debts before saving anything": "",
  "Spend on luxuries before paying bills": "",
  "Pay yourself first means automatically directing a portion of each paycheck to savings and investments before discretionary spending. This ensures consistent wealth building and removes the temptation to spend first and save what remains.": "",
  "A retiree wants $60,000/year in retirement income. Using the 4% rule, how large must their portfolio be?": "",
  "$500,000": "",
  "$1,500,000": "",
  "$2,000,000": "",
  "$1,000,000": "",
  "Required portfolio = Annual income / 0.04 = $60,000 / 0.04 = $1,500,000. Alternatively, multiply desired annual income by 25. This gives a high probability the portfolio lasts at least 30 years.": "",
  "Social Security replaces approximately 40% of pre-retirement income for average earners. If a retiree needs $60,000/year and Social Security provides ~$24,000/year, the annual 'savings gap' they must fund is:": "",
  "$60,000/year": "",
  "$30,000/year": "",
  "$24,000/year": "",
  "$36,000/year": "",
  "Savings gap = $60,000 - $24,000 = $36,000/year must come from personal savings. At 4% rule: $36,000 / 0.04 = $900,000 portfolio needed. Social Security helps but is not enough alone for most retirees.": "",
  "A person with $4,000/month in expenses should have an emergency fund of:": "",
  "$8,000": "",
  "$12,000-$24,000": "",
  "$48,000": "",
  "Emergency fund = 3-6 months of expenses = $4,000 × 3 to $4,000 × 6 = $12,000 to $24,000. The range depends on job stability, dependents, and other factors. Keep in a high-yield savings account for accessibility.": "",
  "A person has $5,000 in credit card debt at 22% APR and wants to know whether to pay it off or invest at an expected 8% return. They should:": "",
  "Pay off the credit card — eliminating 22% guaranteed cost beats an uncertain 8% return": "",
  "Invest — higher potential return over time": "",
  "Do nothing and make minimum payments": "",
  "Split 50/50 between paying debt and investing": "",
  "Paying off 22% debt is a guaranteed 22% return on your money. An 8% investment return is uncertain and lower. Always pay off high-interest debt first — the math is clear: guaranteed 22% > uncertain 8%.": "",
  "A graduate has student loans at 5% and the historical stock market averages 10%. The math suggests they should:": "",
  "Neither invest nor pay extra — spend the money regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "Always pay the loan off first regardless when considering all relevant debt factors": "",
  "Make minimum loan payments and invest the extra, since expected investment return (10%) exceeds loan rate (5%) — but consider risk tolerance": "",
  "Take out more loans to invest, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing debt dynamics": "",
  "When the expected investment return (10%) exceeds the loan rate (5%), investing the difference mathematically makes more. However, guaranteed 5% debt payoff has no risk. This decision also depends on emergency fund status and emotional comfort with debt.": "",
  "A high-yield savings account pays 4.5% and a 1-year CD pays 4.8%. On a $10,000 deposit, the annual difference is:": "",
  "$3": "",
  "$300": "",
  "$30": "",
  "$3,000": "",
  "Difference = $10,000 × (4.8% - 4.5%) = $10,000 × 0.3% = $30/year. For just $30, you lose liquidity with a CD. The savings account lets you access funds anytime, which may be worth more than $30.": "",
  "A couple buys a $300,000 home with 20% down ($60,000). They pay $1,900/month mortgage, $300/month taxes, $150/month insurance, and average $250/month maintenance. True monthly housing cost =": "",
  "$2,600": "",
  "$2,200": "",
  "$1,900": "",
  "Total = $1,900 + $300 + $150 + $250 = $2,600/month. The mortgage payment alone vastly understates the true cost of homeownership. Add property taxes, insurance, and maintenance for the full picture.": "",
  "A new car costs $32,000 and depreciates 60% in 5 years (worth $12,800). A 3-year-old certified pre-owned version costs $20,000 and depreciates to $10,000 over the next 5 years. Which has a lower cost of depreciation?": "",
  "New car — $19,200 depreciation over 5 years": "",
  "Pre-owned — $10,000 depreciation over 5 years, saving $9,200 in lost value": "",
  "New car — it holds value better": "",
  "They depreciate equally": "",
  "New car depreciation = $32,000 - $12,800 = $19,200 lost. Pre-owned depreciation = $20,000 - $10,000 = $10,000 lost. The pre-owned car saves $9,200 in depreciation — the biggest hidden cost of a new car is the initial drop.": "",
  "A 30-year-old earning $80,000 saves 15% of gross income ($12,000/year) in a 401(k) with a 50% employer match up to 6% (match = $2,400/year). At 8% for 35 years to age 65, the total retirement savings equals approximately:": "",
